docs.abstract: In 1918, Ulrich Bonnell Phillips published “American Negro Slavery,” which framed slavery as a labor agreement between masters and happy slaves — facile thinking that persists today.
docs.snippet: In 1918, Ulrich Bonnell Phillips published “American Negro Slavery,” which framed slavery as a labor agreement between masters and happy slaves — facile thinking that persists today.
docs.lead_paragraph: A video of the rapper Kanye West discussing slavery is a sad reminder of America’s historical amnesia about the brutal realities of that institution. “When you hear about slavery for 400 years,” he said in the clip, which was widely circulated on Twitter, “that sounds like a choice.”

headline.main: The Historian Behind Slavery Apologists Like Kanye West

docs.abstract: Barbara Underwood has served as the big thinker for a succession of bosses. Now, with the resignation of her last boss, she is stepping into the spotlight.
docs.snippet: Barbara Underwood has served as the big thinker for a succession of bosses. Now, with the resignation of her last boss, she is stepping into the spotlight.
docs.lead_paragraph: Despite a life of firsts — first in her law-school class, the first woman to serve as the nation’s solicitor general and now the first to serve as New York State’s attorney general — Barbara D. Underwood has spent most of her career as a No. 2.

docs.abstract: The great soprano's birthday, Beethoven and Yanni were among the highlights.
docs.snippet: The great soprano's birthday, Beethoven and Yanni were among the highlights.
docs.lead_paragraph: It’s been a week of loss in music, as two bold composers died: Matt Marks (at just 38) and Glenn Branca (at 69, still too young). Here’s Mr. Mark’s arrangement of the Beatles’ “Revolution 9,” instantly memorable. And Seth Colter Walls guided us through 10 highlights of Mr. Branca’s career, spent in the blurry space between the experimental pop and contemporary classical worlds.

headline.main: The Nilsson Centennial: The Week in Classical Music

docs.abstract: “Incels” are back in the news after the Toronto attack. They may be a fairly small movement, but they tie into a larger phenomenon.

docs.lead_paragraph: The recent mass killing in Toronto by a man who once called for an “Incel Rebellion” has drawn attention to an online community of men who lament being “involuntarily celibate” and dream of a social order granting them access to the women of their choice.

docs.abstract: Laughing at Donald Glover’s sendup of Kanye hasn’t made watching him unravel any less infuriating or devastating.
docs.snippet: Laughing at Donald Glover’s sendup of Kanye hasn’t made watching him unravel any less infuriating or devastating.
docs.lead_paragraph: It seems so long ago, but it has been only a week since Mr. West came out of the closet as the same-dragon-loving, Trump-supporting, slave-shaming, alt-fact fire breather. Last weekend’s “Saturday Night Live,” hosted by the actor and musician Donald Glover, turned Mr. West’s weeklong trolling into the horror film it felt like. But ending the week laughing at Mr. Glover’s sendup of Mr. West hasn’t made watching him unravel any less infuriating or heartbreaking.

docs.abstract: The cult indie rapper smuggled his radical anticapitalism into his biting new film ‘Sorry to Bother You.’
docs.snippet: The cult indie rapper smuggled his radical anticapitalism into his biting new film ‘Sorry to Bother You.’
docs.lead_paragraph: When Boots Riley was done writing the screenplay for his comedy, he figured he needed several name actors and a budget of a few million dollars to actually get it made. He spent decades working as a community organizer, activist and as the frontman of a leftist hip-hop group called the Coup. Riley knew a killer pitch would be necessary: “Trying to get somebody to read your script and you’re a musician?” he asked. “That’s the last person whose script you’re gonna read!”
